## Adding Streaming

Waiting 5–10 seconds for a full response is annoying. Streaming sends tokens as they're generated, so the user sees something immediately.

Add a streaming endpoint:

```javascript
quizRouter.post('/generate-quiz-stream', async (req, res) => {
  const { text } = req.body;

  // Validation (same as before)
  if (!text || text.trim().length < MIN_INPUT_LENGTH) {
    return res.status(400).json({ error: 'Text too short.' });
  }

  // Set headers for Server-Sent Events
  res.setHeader('Content-Type', 'text/event-stream');
  res.setHeader('Cache-Control', 'no-cache');
  res.setHeader('Connection', 'keep-alive');

  try {
    const stream = await client.chat.completions.create({
      model: 'gpt-4o',
      messages: [
        { role: 'system', content: STUDY_BUDDY_SYSTEM_PROMPT },
        { role: 'user', content: `Generate quiz questions from:\n\n${text}` }
      ],
      temperature: 0.3,
      stream: true,  // Enable streaming
    });

    for await (const chunk of stream) {
      const content = chunk.choices[0]?.delta?.content || '';
      if (content) {
        res.write(`data: ${JSON.stringify({ content })}\n\n`);
      }
    }

    res.write('data: [DONE]\n\n');
    res.end();

  } catch (error) {
    res.write(`data: ${JSON.stringify({ error: error.message })}\n\n`);
    res.end();
  }
});
```

> 🐇 **Bunny Tip**
> Streaming JSON is tricky because the JSON arrives in pieces. For the Study Buddy, since we're displaying structured quiz questions, the non-streaming approach is actually fine — we want to show all the questions at once, not character by character. Save streaming for chat-style interactions where partial responses are useful.

---

## What You Just Built

Take a moment to appreciate this. You have:

- A running web server
- An API endpoint that accepts text
- A system prompt that shapes AI behavior
- Input validation that rejects bad data
- AI-powered quiz generation with structured JSON output
- Error handling for all the common failure modes
- Token usage tracking

This is a real backend service. It could handle real users.

> 🔨 **Try It Yourself**
> Use Postman or the curl command above to test your API with at least three different texts:
> 1. A paragraph from a textbook or Wikipedia article
> 2. A very short text (under 100 chars) — should fail validation
> 3. Something that's clearly not educational (a recipe) — what does the AI do?
>
> Observe the responses. Tweak your system prompt based on what you see.

---

## Summary

- Express.js is your web server framework — routes, middleware, request/response handling
- Keep your system prompt in a separate file — it's configuration, not code
- Always validate input before sending to AI — never trust user data
- Use `response_format: json_object` for structured AI output
- Always handle API errors: 429 (rate limit), 401 (auth), 500 (server error)
- Test your API with curl or Postman before building the frontend

